name: Phuntsho
Description: Legend has it that a man carved a woman on a wood just to find the woman come to life the next morning. The woman gave birth to the first man‰Ûªs several children. The origin of the Belly Mask traces back to the mentioned legend. Traditionally, men wear the Belly mask with women clothing and dances during initiation rites and even during the funerals to honor the deceased. Usually in most cases, the belly mask is of a pregnant woman and the male performer dramatizes the agony of child birth. The dance ensures the fertility of the society as a whole.

name: phuntsho
Description: In Ancient Egypt,servants were sacrificed[Office1] whenever someone of great importance died[Office2] . It soon became clear that this practice was a waste of resources so shawabti figures were created as a substitute. A shawabti, which can also be spelled ushebti and shawabti, is a funery figure. Dozens, if not hundreds, of these figures were placed in tombs to serve the deceased in the afterlife.
